                <head>74. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In telegram 2887 from Moscow, May 24, 1961, Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="#p_TLEJ1">Thompson</persName> reported that the previous evening
                    Chairman <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> had told him that “if
                    no agreement [is] reached on Berlin they [Soviet Union] would sign separate
                    peace treaty in fall or winter after [West] German elections and probably after
                    [Soviet] Party Congress. This would end our occupation rights and East Germans
                    would control communications. He realized this would bring period of great
                    tension but he was convinced would not lead to war.” For text of telegram 2887,
                    see <ref target="frus1961-63v14#pg_66">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume XIV, pages
                        66</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v14#pg_69">69</ref>.</p>
            </div>
